Comparing the Presidential Election with the 2024 Paid Sick Leave Referendum

John Verghese

2026-01-08

Paid Sick Leave for Nebraskans and a table of progressive-allied groups, including the AFL-CIO, Planned Parenthood, and the ACLU, supported a referendum mandating paid sick leave for all working Nebraskans. Initiative 436 went on the ballot in the 2024 general election, sharing the ballot with the high-salience presidential election, downballot races, and a number of other ballot measures, including Initiative 439 to codify a womans right to choose. Initiative 436 proved to be the most popular item on the ballot. Nearly 75% of Nebraskans supported the measure1, with all but four counties (which are among the least populous in the state) returning a majority for the measure:

Init 436 Support Population
Keya Paha 43.9% 939
Arthur 47.6% 540
McPherson 48.6% 463
Hayes 49.3% 854
All Other Counties 74.6% 1,963,130

This overwhelming support demonstrates the popularity of progressive economic measures to support working Nebraskans. In every county in the state, Initiative 436 significantly overperformed the top of the Democratic ticket:

Omaha and Lincoln metropolitan counties of Douglas/Sarpy and Lancaster counties, in addition to the majority-Indigenous Thurston County returned the strongest support for the Democratic ticket and the strongest majorities in support of Initiative 436:

There was a strong racial and age correlation with support for the ballot measure, with young, black, and Hispanic counties returning significant support:

In the five counties with more than a quarter of the population identifying as Latino - Colfax, Dakota, Dawson, Hall, and Saline - paid sick leave beat the top of the ticket by ~45 points:

% Latino Population Harris Support Init 436 Support Difference
Colfax 47.3% 10,541 24.0% 69.8% 45.7%
Dakota 41.2% 21,331 34.5% 80.5% 46.0%
Dawson 36.3% 24,020 24.7% 71.2% 46.4%
Hall 31.3% 62,431 30.5% 74.6% 44.1%
Saline 28.7% 14,642 32.8% 72.0% 39.2%

The takeaway: voters in Nebraska across geographies have indicated a willingness to support progressive economic policies. Progressives in Nebraska would do well to strongly associate themselves with the success of Initiative 436, and continue to focus on economically progressive policies.
